  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The victory of the world is indeed not God's aim; therefore His own honour does not suffer that the world of which He has made use in order to chasten His people should for ever haughtily triumph. שׁמך is repeated with emphasis at the end of the petition in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 79:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", according to the figure epanaphora. על־דּבר  equals  למען, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 45:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 7:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is a usage even of the language of the Pentateuch. Also the motive, \"wherefore shall they say?\" occurs even in the Tפra (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 32:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 14:13-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 9:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Here (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 115:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") it originates out of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joel 2:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The wish expressed in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 79:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is based upon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 32:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The poet wishes in company with his contemporaries, as eye-witnesses, to experience what God has promised in the early times, viz., that He will avenge the blood of His servants. The petition in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 32:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " runs like ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 102:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". אסיר individualizingly is those who are carried away captive and incarcerated; בּני תמוּתה are those who, if God does not preserve them by virtue of the greatness (גדל, cf. גּדל ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 15:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of His arm, i.e., of His far-reaching omnipotence, succumb to the power of death as to a patria potestas.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(Note: The Arabic has just this notion in an active application, viz., benı̂ el-môt  equals  the heroes (destroyers) in the battle.)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That the petition in Psalm 79:12 recurs to the neighbouring peoples is explained by the fact, that these, who might most readily come to the knowledge of the God of Israel as the one living and true God, have the greatest degree of guilt on account of their reviling of God. The bosom is mentioned as that in which one takes up and holds that which is handed to him (Luke 6:38); חיק- (על) אל (שׁלּם) השׁיב, as in Isaiah 65:7, Isaiah 65:6; Jeremiah 32:18. A sevenfold requital (cf. Genesis 4:15, Genesis 4:24) is a requital that is fully carried out as a criminal sentence, for seven is the number of a completed process. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "That the petition in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 79:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " recurs to the neighbouring peoples is explained by the fact, that these, who might most readily come to the knowledge of the God of Israel as the one living and true God, have the greatest degree of guilt on account of their reviling of God. The bosom is mentioned as that in which one takes up and holds that which is handed to him (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 6:38",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "); חיק- (על) אל (שׁלּם) השׁיב, as in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 65:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 65:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jeremiah 32:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". A sevenfold requital (cf. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 4:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
